    <node id="Yncheon is an old, broad, and strong edifice that remains standing in the midst of a New England town's street, described as having seven gables and a large clustered chimney. This building, which predates modern structures around it, exudes a human-like quality with its traces of both external and internal experiences. The house has a front gable aligned with the widened street, and in front of it grows an enormous Pyncheon Elm tree, familiar to every town-born child as the Pyncheon Elm.&#10;&#10;The old house was once occupied by a petty huckster who operated a shop from the building's front gable, but since his death, the shop has been locked and closed. Despite its age and deterioration, Yncheon remains an essential part of the town's history, standing as a reminder of its rich past. Its white-oak frame, boards, shingles, crumbling plaster, and even its chimney are just a small part of its reality, as it has witnessed countless experiences and emotions experienced by people within its walls over the years.&#10;&#10;The house's aged appearance is contrasted by the surrounding modern habitations which are smaller, built entirely of wood, and lacking in any picturesque quality that would draw attention to their histories. Yncheon's faded grandeur, however, continues to attract the imagination and sympathy of those who pass it by." />
