    <node id="The old Pyncheon engaged in small-scale commercial operations, possibly as a petty huckster. He was so involved in the day-to-day business that he would give change for a shilling and verify half-pennies with his own hands. His shop was located on the side of the Pyncheon House, and it has been closed since his death, about a century before the story's events. The shop door became a source of embarrassment for the Pyncheon family members, including the current occupant of the Pyncheon House.&#10;&#10;The old counter, shelves, and other fixtures remain intact as they were when he left them. There was a belief that the dead shopkeeper would appear in a white wig, faded velvet coat, apron, and dusty shoes near the shop door. The shop's interior has likely undergone little change over time.&#10;&#10;It is worth noting that the old Pyncheon's commercial endeavors might have been influenced by the contemporary practice of merchants storing goods and transacting business in their own dwellings, which was common during his lifetime. The shop's continued closure reflects the family's social standing and shifting priorities away from commercial activities." />
