    <node id="Yes, it is highly likely that the secluded old bachelor would have felt compelled to make amends for his ancestor's wrongdoing by restoring the House of the Seven Gables to Maule's descendant. The old bachelor was depicted as a man who lived in the past and placed great importance on right and wrong. He believed that it was improper for him to be in possession of the house, which he referred to as ill-gotten spoil with a black stain of blood. This shows that he was troubled by the unjust death of Matthew Maule and his family's role in it.&#10;&#10;Moreover, he had brought himself to the conclusion that Matthew Maule had been wronged out of his homestead and wealth, which added to his guilt. He even feared that by holding onto the house, he was committing the same wrong as his ancestor and incurring all its original responsibilities. The only reason he did not go through with returning the house to Maule's descendant was due to the uproar caused by his relatives, who were concerned about their legal tenure of the property.&#10;&#10;Therefore, it can be inferred that if not for this external pressure from his family, the old bachelor would have made amends for his ancestor's wrongdoing by returning the House of the Seven Gables to Maule's descendant." />
