    <node id="According to tradition, Colonel Pyncheon had a plausible claim to the proprietorship of a desirable piece of land, which had been granted to him by the legislature. This land was previously occupied by an obscure man named Matthew Maule, who had cultivated it and turned it into his homestead. The dispute between the two men over this land lasted for several years, as Matthew Maule stubbornly defended what he considered his right to the property. Although there is no written record of the dispute, it is believed that Colonel Pyncheon's claim may have been unduly stretched to cover Matthew Maule's small piece of land. The controversy remained undecided for many years and only came to a close with Matthew Maule's death, which occurred under strange and horrifying circumstances." />
