    <edge source="Yes, it is highly likely that the secluded old bachelor would have felt compelled to make amends for his ancestor's wrongdoing by restoring the House of the Seven Gables to Maule's descendant. The old bachelor was depicted as a man who lived in the past and placed great importance on right and wrong. He believed that it was improper for him to be in possession of the house, which he referred to as ill-gotten spoil with a black stain of blood. This shows that he was troubled by the unjust death of Matthew Maule and his family's role in it.&#10;&#10;Moreover, he had brought himself to the conclusion that Matthew Maule had been wronged out of his homestead and wealth, which added to his guilt. He even feared that by holding onto the house, he was committing the same wrong as his ancestor and incurring all its original responsibilities. The only reason he did not go through with returning the house to Maule's descendant was due to the uproar caused by his relatives, who were concerned about their legal tenure of the property.&#10;&#10;Therefore, it can be inferred that if not for this external pressure from his family, the old bachelor would have made amends for his ancestor's wrongdoing by returning the House of the Seven Gables to Maule's descendant." target=" in possession of&#10;    the ill-gotten spoil,--with the black stain of blood sunken deep into&#10;    it, and still to be scented by conscientious nostrils,--the question&#10;    occurred, whether it were not imperative upon him, even at this late&#10;    hour, to make restitution to Maule's posterity.  To a man living so&#10;    much in the past, and so little in the present, as the secluded and&#10;    antiquarian old bachelor, a century and a half seemed not so vast a&#10;    period as to obviate the propriety of substituting right for wrong.  It&#10;    was the belief of those who knew him best, that he would positively&#10;    have taken the very singular step of giving up the House of the Seven&#10;    Gables to the representative of Matthew Maule, but for the unspeakable&#10;    tumult which a suspicion of the old gentleman's project awakened among&#10;    his Pyncheon relatives.  Their exertions had the effect of suspending&#10;    his purpose; but it was feared that he would perform, after death,">
