    <edge source="The superstition surrounding the Pyncheon family about having &quot;Maule's blood to drink&quot; and being haunted by a generational curse originates from the historical feud between Colonel Pyncheon and the wizard Matthew Maule. The feud culminated in Matthew Maule's execution, during which he allegedly cursed Colonel Pyncheon and his descendants with the words, &quot;God hath given him blood to drink!&quot;&#10;&#10;This supernatural allusion became intertwined with the popular imagination and was perpetuated by the mysterious circumstances of Colonel Pyncheon's sudden death in the House of the Seven Gables. The signs of struggle, a bloody handprint on his ruff, and blood on his beard led people to suspect foul play or even supernatural involvement.&#10;&#10;Further fueling these rumors was the persistent belief that Matthew Maule's grave was built upon during the construction of the House of the Seven Gables. This perceived desecration of Maule's burial site might have contributed to the mansion being haunted by his ghost, as suggested by the change in quality of the water from Maule's Well and the eerie reference to Matthew Maule at the scene of Colonel Pyncheon's death.&#10;&#10;Over time, these events and rumors evolved into a superstition that the Pyncheon family had 'Maule's blood to drink' as part of their inheritance, signifying that they were haunted by an evil influence or the presence of a dead progenitor who had become their Evil Genius." target="The large mirror in the House of the Seven Gables is said to contain the reflections of all its inhabitants, past and present. This belief may have originated from the family's oral history or superstition. However, there is a specific story connecting Matthew Maule's descendants to this mirror.&#10;&#10;According to the tale, Matthew Maule's offspring claimed to have some connection to the mystery of the looking-glass through a mesmeric process. They believed they could animate its inner region and reveal the Pyncheons in an unfavorable light. The rumors suggest that the posterity of Matthew Maule had the ability to make the mirror show the Pyncheons reenacting their sins or misdeeds, not as they appeared to the world but in a more negative aspect.&#10;&#10;This belief might have stemmed from the longstanding feud and animosity between the two families, with Matthew Maule's descendants holding grudges or seeking retribution for the alleged land theft by Colonel Pyncheon and the execution of their ancestor. The mirror then became a symbolic representation of the Pyncheons' guilt or an embodiment of their haunted past.&#10;&#10;It is essential to note that these are stories and rumors without a solid foundation, but they contribute to the eerie atmosphere and mysterious allure surrounding the House of the Seven Gables and its inhabitants, the Pyncheon family.">
